15:23.156 --> 15:25.258
- [Michael R.] I
found in most cases

15:25.358 --> 15:27.494
people that you're going
to dangerous things with

15:27.594 --> 15:28.895
and break the law,

15:28.996 --> 15:30.597
you better be close friends.

15:30.697 --> 15:33.933
You better be sure that
you got each other's back.

15:34.034 --> 15:36.703
- You know, a goal was
not the drug business,

15:36.803 --> 15:38.571
it just morphed
into this, you know,

15:38.671 --> 15:39.939
it went from a group,

15:40.040 --> 15:42.609
a handful of guys seeking
spiritual enlightenment,

15:42.709 --> 15:45.212
to next thing you know,
we were smuggling.

15:45.312 --> 15:46.579
- First it started
off small things,

15:46.679 --> 15:49.349
but then the loads kept
getting bigger, bigger,

15:49.449 --> 15:52.585
which was more revenue.

15:52.685 --> 15:55.088
The money for the
LSD all went back in

15:55.188 --> 15:56.589
to make more to make it cheaper,

15:56.689 --> 15:59.292
give it away for almost nothing.

15:59.392 --> 16:06.333
(funky music)

16:06.433 --> 16:09.536
- People on the east coast
pay like five times more money

16:09.636 --> 16:12.572
than we do on the west
coast for marijuana,

16:12.672 --> 16:14.474
so however you
get it back there,

16:14.574 --> 16:19.379
you can make quite
a bit of money.

16:19.479 --> 16:21.414
Used to be able to
go to the airport

16:21.514 --> 16:24.917
and say, "Hi my name is"
whatever name you want.

16:25.018 --> 16:28.588
Go on a one way ticket,
take a large suitcase,

16:28.688 --> 16:30.123
fill it with weed.

16:30.223 --> 16:33.093
Check it into baggage on the
airplane, fly it to New York.

16:33.193 --> 16:34.661
You could do that.

16:34.761 --> 16:36.663
- [Ron] At this time, you
could get on a plane anywhere,

16:36.763 --> 16:39.332
and whatever you had
on your body was fine.

16:48.041 --> 16:52.445
- All the Afghani hash was
known as Primo, Afghani Primo.

16:52.545 --> 16:55.082
One of my reasons for
exploring the hash business

16:55.182 --> 16:56.849
was I loved it so much,

16:56.949 --> 16:58.318
but it was so expensive.

16:58.418 --> 17:00.087
I mean you pretty much
had to be a dealer

17:00.187 --> 17:01.788
to be able to afford to use it,

17:01.888 --> 17:03.756
so I wanted to make it cheaper.

17:03.856 --> 17:06.025
(dramatic music)

17:06.126 --> 17:07.294
I just started doing
a little research

17:07.394 --> 17:08.661
on where they had hash,

17:08.761 --> 17:11.598
figured it out and
decided to go do a ...

17:11.698 --> 17:13.200
I got Ricky Bevells
to go with me

17:13.300 --> 17:15.602
and we flew to Europe,

17:15.702 --> 17:19.539
clean cut, corduroy sport
jackets, and short hair.

17:19.638 --> 17:20.839
- [Voiceover] We decided
we'd go to Germany

17:20.940 --> 17:26.713
and buy a car, and
drive to Nepal.

17:26.813 --> 17:29.282
Since we both had hid
cars with door panels

17:29.382 --> 17:30.483
from Mexico and everything,

17:30.583 --> 17:32.185
we thought okay,
well we'll get a car,

17:32.285 --> 17:34.521
score and fill it
up, and ship it home.

17:34.621 --> 17:36.656
We had no idea
where we were going,

17:36.756 --> 17:39.226
or what we were
going to encounter.

17:39.326 --> 17:41.794
- We picked up a couple
hippies that were hitchhiking.

17:41.894 --> 17:43.130
It was a guy and a girl.

17:43.230 --> 17:45.365
So, we started smoking
with these hippies,

17:45.465 --> 17:47.134
and one thing came to another,

17:47.234 --> 17:48.668
and they figured out
we were coming there

17:48.768 --> 17:49.902
to get some hash.

17:50.002 --> 17:51.471
So the guys says,
"You know what, man?"

17:51.571 --> 17:54.841
He says, "You wanna
go to Afghanistan."

17:54.941 --> 17:57.009
And I said, "Where the
heck, where's that?"

17:57.110 --> 17:59.011
I had never heard of that.

17:59.112 --> 18:01.181
He says, "They got the best
hash in the world there,

18:01.281 --> 18:02.982
"and it's only four
dollars a kilo."

18:03.082 --> 18:04.717
I said, "When do we leave, man?"

18:04.817 --> 18:08.988
And the next morning, man,
we headed for Afghanistan.

18:09.088 --> 18:10.590
- [Voiceover] We
were very young,

18:10.690 --> 18:14.727
and not very fearful of
hardly anything, actually.

18:14.827 --> 18:16.196
We weren't two kids,

18:16.296 --> 18:19.232
like you think of a 19
year old and a 20 year old.

18:19.332 --> 18:20.600
It was different than that,

18:20.700 --> 18:22.602
because we had been weekly

18:22.702 --> 18:26.806
tapping into this
self that is eternal.

18:26.906 --> 18:28.208
And we knew that.

18:28.308 --> 18:31.878
So, we were like, old
souls in young bodies

18:31.978 --> 18:36.449
going over to do this deed.

18:36.549 --> 18:37.750
- When we first got there,

18:37.850 --> 18:39.186
we were standing in
line at this fruit stand

18:39.286 --> 18:40.720
to buy some fruit,

18:40.820 --> 18:42.755
when this guy comes
walking across the square,

18:42.855 --> 18:43.956
looking right at us.

18:44.056 --> 18:46.092
And I see kind of a guy
in a turban, you know,

18:46.193 --> 18:47.694
and he comes right
up to us and goes,

18:47.794 --> 18:50.630
"Would you guys like to
buy some fine Afghan shit?"

18:50.730 --> 18:52.532
I said, "What kind of
shit you got, man?"

18:52.632 --> 18:55.602
He said, "Well, I
got cocaine, hashish,

18:55.702 --> 18:58.205
"morphine, opium."

18:58.305 --> 19:02.975
I go, "Well, that
hash sounds good."

19:03.075 --> 19:04.911
We'd gone on this
trip originally

19:05.011 --> 19:06.813
planning on trying
to get 10 kilos.

19:06.913 --> 19:08.881
22 pounds, that was our goal.

19:08.981 --> 19:12.051
We ended up buying 50
kilos from these guys.

19:12.151 --> 19:15.788
This is Ayatoolah and
Nazareem, two po-ki brothers.

19:15.888 --> 19:17.424
So, we had all this hash,

19:17.524 --> 19:19.459
We were gonna figure out, how
are we gonna get this home?

19:19.559 --> 19:21.928
So, we started
going to the bazaar,

19:22.028 --> 19:23.996
looking at antiques and stuff.

19:24.096 --> 19:26.065
And things were so
ridiculously cheap.

19:26.165 --> 19:28.901
We found all these beautiful
antique musical instruments,

19:29.001 --> 19:31.471
drums, and like tablas,

19:31.571 --> 19:35.007
and stringed instruments
like tambouras.

19:35.107 --> 19:37.644
We just bought a bunch of it
and we packed it with hash.

19:37.744 --> 19:38.745
You could pack the neck.

19:38.845 --> 19:41.147
You could line the body of it.

19:41.248 --> 19:42.849
- [Voiceover] We saw
it in the news paper,

19:42.949 --> 19:45.852
that they had executed
a Canadian guy

19:45.952 --> 19:48.288
for possession of a very
small amount of hash.

19:48.388 --> 19:52.325
So, we didn't realize we
were risking our lives.

19:52.425 --> 19:54.327
- So, I'm sitting out in Pomona.

19:54.427 --> 19:56.629
Travis and Rick, he
called me from Europe.

19:56.729 --> 19:59.832
And they proceed to tell me
that they sent me a shipment,

19:59.932 --> 20:01.634
and the hash is in
it and it's coming,

20:01.734 --> 20:03.803
and I have to go pick it
up from the LA Customs.

20:03.903 --> 20:05.438
Why'd they send it to me?

20:05.538 --> 20:07.607
I didn't tell them they
could send that to me.

20:07.707 --> 20:09.342
Why the fuck did
they send that to me?

20:09.442 --> 20:12.111
Why didn't they
send it to themself.

20:12.211 --> 20:14.046
So, I go to the
airport, pick this up.

20:14.146 --> 20:16.616
Well, they had sent animal skins

20:16.716 --> 20:19.286
with all the instruments that
they packed the hash into.

20:19.386 --> 20:20.487
They hassled me about the skins.

20:20.587 --> 20:21.621
They said, "You can't
import these skins.

20:21.721 --> 20:23.022
"What are you guys doin'?"

20:23.122 --> 20:24.524
And I'm standing there with
these two customs agents

20:24.624 --> 20:26.726
for hours when they've got
this stuff all over the floor.

20:26.826 --> 20:28.227
- [Voiceover] It wasn't
over till it was over.

20:28.328 --> 20:31.331
So, until Ron had cleared
it, we were all ahead.

20:31.431 --> 20:33.400
I was worried about my
brother getting busted.

20:33.500 --> 20:34.867
Ron was worried
about getting busted.

20:34.967 --> 20:38.305
Trav was probably worried
that we'd lose everything.

20:38.405 --> 20:41.808
- And the one guy picks
up the one wooden tabla,

20:41.908 --> 20:44.711
the drum, and he says,
"This thing's heavy.

20:44.811 --> 20:46.746
"He says, it must
be solid wood."

20:46.846 --> 20:48.981
And other customs agents
picks up another one,

20:49.081 --> 20:51.818
and said, "Yeah, and I
suppose this is solid metal."

20:51.918 --> 20:53.553
And they're looking
at each other.

20:53.653 --> 20:55.221
And I'm just standing there.

20:55.322 --> 20:59.592
They said, okay, you can go.

20:59.692 --> 21:01.894
- So, we showed up
with 88 pounds of hash

21:01.994 --> 21:03.830
that nobody even knew
that hash was like that.

21:03.930 --> 21:04.897
It was so good,
so different

21:04.997 --> 21:06.699
than anything we'd
ever seen before.

21:06.799 --> 21:08.835
There's, it's the best
hash in the world.

21:08.935 --> 21:12.672
(serene music)

21:12.772 --> 21:16.609
- I'm in Ann Arbor
at a college commune,

21:16.709 --> 21:18.978
and I walk in,

21:19.078 --> 21:24.617
and this wonderful
aroma wharfs past me,

21:24.717 --> 21:27.920
and it was almost like
a moment, you know,

21:28.020 --> 21:29.856
that I really, to this day,

21:29.956 --> 21:31.724
I mean how many
years ago was that?

21:31.824 --> 21:34.694
45 or something, 50 years ago,

21:34.794 --> 21:36.863
and I'm still thinking
of when I think of it.

21:36.963 --> 21:40.533
It really is a moment of wow.

21:40.633 --> 21:41.868
And I said, "This
stuff's really good.

21:41.968 --> 21:43.102
"Where'd you get it?"

21:43.202 --> 21:44.771
And he said,

21:44.871 --> 21:47.974
"These people called The
Brotherhood bring it in."

21:48.074 --> 21:51.411
And I said, "There's people
called The Brotherhood?"

21:51.511 --> 21:55.081
(laughs) And I said,
"Well, that sounds cool."

21:55.181 --> 21:56.949
- [Voiceover] People were
associating this hash

21:57.049 --> 21:59.285
from Afghanistan
with the Brotherhood,

21:59.386 --> 22:00.920
because we were the
ones that had it.

22:01.020 --> 22:03.823
And the name Brotherhood
probably went along with it.

22:03.923 --> 22:05.224
It was dealt in pounds.

22:05.324 --> 22:06.893
Then it was dealt in ounces.

22:06.993 --> 22:09.562
Then it was dealt
in grams, you know.

22:09.662 --> 22:11.998
- Everybody had to have some,

22:12.098 --> 22:15.435
and then of course that just
set everyone to thinking,

22:15.535 --> 22:20.206
we can do this, you know?

22:20.306 --> 22:24.977
John and I had started to
pursue the idea of providing

22:25.077 --> 22:28.981
massive amounts of LSD,
as much acid as we could.

22:29.081 --> 22:31.083
- [Voiceover] We went
through a number phases

22:31.183 --> 22:33.920
where we got different
types of LSD.

22:34.020 --> 22:37.356
There was 7th Chakra
Lavendar, Blue Levis.

22:37.457 --> 22:40.026
There was Red Tab.

22:40.126 --> 22:42.128
- Ram Dass, who was
Richard Alpert's said,

22:42.228 --> 22:43.496
"You guys need a center.

22:43.596 --> 22:47.700
"You need a place to
explain how you're

22:47.800 --> 22:48.768
"surviving."

22:48.868 --> 22:50.937
Because now we're selling acid.

22:51.037 --> 22:53.606
* Pack too much baby

22:53.706 --> 22:54.974
* Say you'll be my girl

22:55.074 --> 22:58.144
- [Michael R.] So, we
went to Laguna Beach.

22:58.244 --> 23:01.414
It was an artist colony.

23:01.514 --> 23:05.317
It was the most liberal of
places in Orange County.

23:05.418 --> 23:07.186
Who doesn't like the beach?

23:07.286 --> 23:09.656
* Back again let me in

23:09.756 --> 23:11.991
* The war is over
where you been *

23:12.091 --> 23:14.326
- Johnny and I started
immediately talking

23:14.427 --> 23:16.395
that a bookstore,

23:16.496 --> 23:17.997
a metaphysical bookstore,

23:18.097 --> 23:20.199
that's what we were gonna do.

23:20.299 --> 23:24.403
And we then found the place
on Pacific Coast Highway

23:24.504 --> 23:27.173
that was just way bigger
than a bookstore place,

23:27.273 --> 23:28.407
but it looked perfect

23:28.508 --> 23:30.810
and the whole thing
just expanded out like,

23:30.910 --> 23:32.011
"Well, hell let's

23:32.111 --> 23:34.046
"put a bookstore here
and other stores there."

23:34.146 --> 23:36.148
It became a bigger vision.

23:36.248 --> 23:39.919
- And that way we
could be creative and

23:40.019 --> 23:42.021
more hide what we were doing.

23:42.121 --> 23:44.691
* Walk right by
the old news baby *

23:44.791 --> 23:46.893
- A clothing store,
handmade clothing,

23:46.993 --> 23:50.162
there was a bead
store, art gallery,

23:50.262 --> 23:52.064
a health food juice bar,

23:52.164 --> 23:54.066
and we called it
Mystic Arts World.

23:54.166 --> 23:55.668
And it was a hit,

23:55.768 --> 23:58.004
and the place started
making money from day one.

23:58.104 --> 24:00.172
* Hey hey hey hey

24:00.272 --> 24:02.709
* No no no no

24:02.809 --> 24:05.512
- [Michael R.] The
Los Angeles Times said

24:05.612 --> 24:08.881
that, "Mystic Arts World
was the finest gallery

24:08.981 --> 24:10.917
"in southern California."

24:11.017 --> 24:12.852
There was nothing
like it around.

24:12.952 --> 24:14.854
There has never been
anything like it around.

24:14.954 --> 24:18.591
It was a psychedelic emporium.

24:18.691 --> 24:20.126
- [Travis] Mystic
Arts became the center

24:20.226 --> 24:21.127
for southern California

24:21.227 --> 24:22.361
for the hippie movement,

24:22.461 --> 24:23.630
and the psychedelic movement,

24:23.730 --> 24:25.231
the spiritual movement,

24:25.331 --> 24:27.033
and Laguna became the
town everyone flocked to.

24:27.133 --> 24:29.869
It was like Haight
Ashbury south.

24:29.969 --> 24:32.138
And we ended calling
the place Dodge City,

24:32.238 --> 24:34.106
because of everybody
was dealing pot,

24:34.206 --> 24:35.875
and psychedelics, and just,

24:35.975 --> 24:40.613
I mean, it became the place.

24:40.713 --> 24:42.549
- [Carol] There was no
law there, you know.

24:42.649 --> 24:44.050
It was the wild west,

24:44.150 --> 24:45.217
and a new frontier.

24:45.317 --> 24:47.253
You know, it was
our own community.

24:47.353 --> 24:48.921
- [Michael R.] It
was like the Shire,

24:49.021 --> 24:53.660
this beautiful idyllic
little weird community.

24:53.760 --> 24:55.261
- [Voiceover] You could
just go out on the street,

24:55.361 --> 24:56.395
and you'd run into
somebody you knew,

24:56.495 --> 24:57.997
and have a conversation,

24:58.097 --> 24:59.932
or go over to their house
and smoke a joint with them,

25:00.032 --> 25:01.734
or get some waves, go surfing.

25:01.834 --> 25:05.271
It was all so relaxed
and sort of utopia.

25:05.371 --> 25:08.274
- [Carol] Johnny used to
love to take acid and surf.

25:08.374 --> 25:10.142
That was their whole thing.

25:10.242 --> 25:11.644
That's what got 'em all goin'.

25:11.744 --> 25:14.981
A lot of the surfers, they
called it Christ in the curl.

25:15.081 --> 25:18.117
- You had surfers meeting
with all the hippies

25:18.217 --> 25:19.518
and everybody smoked weed.

25:19.619 --> 25:20.920
Everybody took acid.

25:21.020 --> 25:23.055
Everybody did.

25:23.155 --> 25:25.324
- [Carol] Chuch Wendell
had brought Mike Hynson

25:25.424 --> 25:28.360
out to the canyon to meet us.

25:28.460 --> 25:30.196
- Mike Hynson was
the best surfer

25:30.296 --> 25:32.431
in the world,
practically in the day,

25:32.531 --> 25:36.035
and a movie star, kind of.

25:36.135 --> 25:39.839
His story on black
speech in San Diego once,

25:39.939 --> 25:41.440
we're passing a
joint back and forth,

25:41.540 --> 25:43.042
both high on acid,

25:43.142 --> 25:44.476
and Mike picked up his board,

25:44.577 --> 25:48.147
and he jumps in the water
with the joint still lit,

25:48.247 --> 25:50.016
jumps into this wave,

25:50.116 --> 25:52.051
catches it just perfect,

25:52.151 --> 25:55.287
and he disappeared
inside the curl,

25:55.387 --> 25:56.723
and sitting on the
beach, can't see him.

25:56.823 --> 25:58.390
And all of a sudden
he comes flying out

25:58.490 --> 26:01.527
the back end of the wave
kind of sitting cross-legged

26:01.628 --> 26:03.830
on the back of the surfboard,

26:03.930 --> 26:07.533
and hops off, grabs
the surfboard,

26:07.634 --> 26:13.773
and the joint is still lit.

26:13.873 --> 26:16.843
He said, "That's how you're
supposed to do it, brother."

26:16.943 --> 26:19.612
You know, it was like, my God.

26:27.620 --> 26:30.356
- Selling psychedelics
was a dharmic way to be.

26:30.456 --> 26:32.358
It was a good way
to make a living.

26:32.458 --> 26:33.492
It was honest.

26:33.592 --> 26:35.527
It was a good product.

26:35.628 --> 26:37.997
It was wanted, you know.

26:38.097 --> 26:43.169
The only problem
is it was illegal.

26:43.269 --> 26:45.271
- Because they made it illegal,

26:45.371 --> 26:47.273
it produced commerce.

26:47.373 --> 26:49.075
All the hippies can't
be just smoking weed

26:49.175 --> 26:50.009
and taking LSD.

26:50.109 --> 26:52.011
Someone has to make the money.

26:52.111 --> 26:53.345
Now there was bands.

26:53.445 --> 26:54.681
There was health food stores.

26:54.781 --> 26:55.915
There was record shops,

26:56.015 --> 26:58.250
but the main commerce
came from the LSD,

26:58.350 --> 27:00.186
the marijuana, and the hashish.

27:00.286 --> 27:01.754
From the smugglers
to the ground dealer,

27:01.854 --> 27:03.455
this started a commerce

27:03.555 --> 27:10.262
that allowed the hippie
movement to happen.

27:10.362 --> 27:11.397
- [Carol] The movement

27:11.497 --> 27:13.565
and the name of The Brotherhood

27:13.666 --> 27:15.301
kept getting bigger and bigger.

27:15.401 --> 27:18.404
- And I think a lot of
people realized that

27:18.504 --> 27:21.774
we were gonna be
a major influence

27:21.874 --> 27:24.476
in the psychedelic world.

27:30.516 --> 27:31.884
- I was an attorney.

27:31.984 --> 27:34.486
I had been practicing
for a number of years.

27:34.586 --> 27:37.924
We were representing a lot of
draft resisters at the time

27:38.024 --> 27:40.793
and a lot of drug
dealers at the time.

27:40.893 --> 27:42.829
My basic view of the law was

27:42.929 --> 27:45.297
anybody our
government didn't like

27:45.397 --> 27:46.598
couldn't be all bad.

27:46.699 --> 27:49.501
So, we represented criminals.

27:49.601 --> 27:51.838
We were very
political ourselves,

27:51.938 --> 27:57.176
very proud student activists.

27:57.276 --> 27:59.445
- [Michael R.] I mean,
I think the 60s was

27:59.545 --> 28:02.448
the perfect storm
in so many ways.

28:02.548 --> 28:04.316
With all the
background of people

28:04.416 --> 28:06.819
just getting sick
and tired of racism,

28:06.919 --> 28:10.089
women wanting to be
treated more equally

28:10.189 --> 28:11.924
in society and they weren't.

28:12.024 --> 28:13.793
- [Carol] It was
during the Vietnam War.

28:13.893 --> 28:16.328
You know, nobody wanted
to go fight the war.

28:16.428 --> 28:17.296
Nobody wanted to do that.

28:17.396 --> 28:19.165
It was all about peace and love.

28:19.265 --> 28:21.367
- You had the marches going on.

28:21.467 --> 28:23.435
They know it was,

28:23.535 --> 28:25.437
a lot of turmoil.

28:25.537 --> 28:27.639
- Great steps forward often come

28:27.740 --> 28:30.542
from a surprising stimulus.

28:30.642 --> 28:33.946
Psychedelics was just the
catalyst you drop into it,

28:34.046 --> 28:37.817
and it all started to
gel and come together.

28:37.917 --> 28:39.351
People just said,

28:39.451 --> 28:41.387
"We're not gonna put
up with this anymore.

28:41.487 --> 28:46.092
"This isn't right,
and so we rebuild."

28:46.192 --> 28:50.696
(upbeat music)

28:50.797 --> 28:53.032
We were there for
the Berkeley riots.

28:53.132 --> 28:55.234
- [Voiceover] 400 police
officers moved skirmish lines

28:55.334 --> 28:56.535
through the area.

28:56.635 --> 28:58.337
- My beautiful girls
would run around topless,

28:58.437 --> 29:00.672
and give the soldiers flowers,

29:00.773 --> 29:03.242
and sometimes refreshments

29:03.342 --> 29:05.511
that were laced with
acid, of course.

29:05.611 --> 29:07.814
There were times
when we'd go out,

29:07.914 --> 29:11.083
and this roadblock
isn't there anymore.

29:11.183 --> 29:14.186
All the guards are layin'
on the lawns of the houses,

29:14.286 --> 29:15.554
in their uniform,

29:15.654 --> 29:18.357
with their stupid looking
old bolt action rifles,

29:18.457 --> 29:19.892
flowers in the stock,

29:19.992 --> 29:22.494
and they're as loaded
as they could be.

29:22.594 --> 29:25.264
There was a time, particularly
in southern California,

29:25.364 --> 29:26.565
where word spread.

29:26.665 --> 29:28.434
It was mostly mythology,

29:28.534 --> 29:32.338
The Brotherhood of Eternal
Love could take a tab of acid,

29:32.438 --> 29:34.240
and with a little
pair of gloves,

29:34.340 --> 29:36.242
they'd put it on your doorknob.

29:36.342 --> 29:38.377
They could put it in
your drinking water.

29:38.477 --> 29:40.346
They could put it everywhere,

29:40.446 --> 29:42.448
and you didn't even
know it had hit you

29:42.548 --> 29:44.083
until you were stoned
outta your mind,

29:44.183 --> 29:45.584
and wondering, "Whoa!

29:45.684 --> 29:50.022
"Why am I looking into the
face of God all of a sudden?"

29:50.122 --> 29:52.524
- [Voiceover] We were on a
mission to change the world,

29:52.624 --> 29:55.427
and we were doing it by
supplying psychedelics

29:55.527 --> 29:57.263
to help change
people's thinking.

29:57.363 --> 29:59.098
So, it was worth the risk.

29:59.198 --> 30:00.766
- It began a year ago,

30:00.867 --> 30:03.035
when to so-called
free speech advocates,

30:03.135 --> 30:05.471
who in truth have no
appreciation for freedom,

30:05.571 --> 30:07.306
were allowed to
assault and humiliate

30:07.406 --> 30:08.941
the symbol of law and
order of policemen

30:09.041 --> 30:10.209
on the campus.

30:10.309 --> 30:11.477
- What we were doing
became political

30:11.577 --> 30:13.779
because it influenced
so many people.

30:13.880 --> 30:16.382
- This year, I will
propose a drug control act,

30:16.482 --> 30:18.117
to provide stricter penalties

30:18.217 --> 30:21.687
for those who traffic in LSD,

30:21.787 --> 30:25.124
and other dangerous
drugs with our people.

30:25.224 --> 30:28.560
The time has come
to stop the sale

30:28.660 --> 30:30.562
of slavery to the young.

30:30.662 --> 30:32.564
- The war on drugs
was a war on us.

30:32.664 --> 30:35.434
The war on drugs is a
war on psychedelics,

30:35.534 --> 30:37.569
things that they cannot control.

30:37.669 --> 30:39.805
- [Voiceover] 20,000 young
people filled the canyon

30:39.906 --> 30:42.508
outside the resort
town of Laguna Beach.

30:42.608 --> 30:44.944
They came by the thousands
to sleep on the ground,

30:45.044 --> 30:46.612
or in their cars and campers.

30:46.712 --> 30:47.846
- [Voiceover] We were
starting to realize

30:47.947 --> 30:49.615
that more and more
people shared the vision

30:49.715 --> 30:51.483
that we'd had, which was great.

30:51.583 --> 30:53.452
Think, "Oh, yeah,
this is really good.

30:53.552 --> 30:54.653
"You know, it's spreading.

30:54.753 --> 30:56.355
"It's spreading like we
were hoping it would."

30:56.455 --> 30:59.425
- Drugs are just an
everyday part of life here.

30:59.525 --> 31:01.360
It's a special day
that it's really happy

31:01.460 --> 31:06.332
and a lot of people and
a lot of brotherhood.

31:06.432 --> 31:09.001
- I had come to Laguna,

31:09.101 --> 31:11.637
and I wanted to get more hash.

31:11.737 --> 31:13.705
While I was there,
I had met everyone,

31:13.805 --> 31:16.042
and everyone was really nice,

31:16.142 --> 31:19.611
but I was wondering, you know,

31:19.711 --> 31:21.713
where's the Brotherhood?

31:21.813 --> 31:23.282
Who's the Brotherhood?

31:23.382 --> 31:25.884
You know, they were
supposedly the people who,

31:25.985 --> 31:27.886
who get this and I actually,

31:27.987 --> 31:31.357
had kind of paid
for that connection.

31:31.457 --> 31:33.559
So, I wanted to, I wanted,

31:33.659 --> 31:36.062
I didn't want to go
through other people.

31:36.162 --> 31:37.997
- [Voiceover] The rock
lovers keep coming.

31:38.097 --> 31:39.531
They leave their cars and walk.

31:39.631 --> 31:44.803
- The last of '66,
'67, and into '68,

31:44.903 --> 31:48.374
Laguna was like an anthill,

31:48.474 --> 31:51.710
and just, just these hippy-types

31:51.810 --> 31:55.447
just buzzin' around.

31:55.547 --> 31:57.183
I'll never forget my first time

31:57.283 --> 31:58.917
I actually parked there,

31:59.018 --> 32:00.919
and I walked down at sunset.

32:01.020 --> 32:02.554
It was about 7:00 at night,

32:02.654 --> 32:05.257
and I looked out there,

32:05.357 --> 32:07.559
and as far as you
could see both ways,

32:07.659 --> 32:10.396
there was more potheads
down there smokin'

32:10.496 --> 32:13.199
watchin' the sun goin'
down cross-legged,

32:13.299 --> 32:14.566
"Om ...

32:14.666 --> 32:16.768
"Om ..."

32:16.868 --> 32:21.140
And I'm just thinkin',
"You know, nothing.

32:21.240 --> 32:23.675
"I guess this is just
a free wide open place,

32:23.775 --> 32:25.077
"but this is bull.

32:25.177 --> 32:26.512
"Marijuana's a felony.

32:26.612 --> 32:28.514
"All these other
drugs are felonies."

32:28.614 --> 32:30.949
And I'm gonna,

32:31.050 --> 32:33.185
I'm going to make
it my business.

32:38.224 --> 32:41.227
The orders of the police
department at that time was,

32:41.327 --> 32:44.296
we're gonna write as many
tickets as we can write,

32:44.396 --> 32:46.698
and we're gonna make as
many arrests as you can.

32:46.798 --> 32:51.603
That's all there is to it.

32:51.703 --> 32:53.272
- [Voiceover] Well,
we opened up the shop,

32:53.372 --> 32:55.307
and people started
coming from all around,

32:55.407 --> 32:57.576
and hanging out on the
sidewalk in front there,

32:57.676 --> 32:59.978
and smoking pot
and getting busted.

33:00.079 --> 33:02.248
It just slowly sort of built up,

33:02.348 --> 33:03.615
that notoriety,

33:03.715 --> 33:05.284
which brought
people like Purcell

33:05.384 --> 33:07.986
to start trying to
observe us more closely.

33:08.087 --> 33:10.089
You know, from behind
the bushes and stuff,

33:10.189 --> 33:13.725
watching.

33:13.825 --> 33:16.262
- By now, we had a reputation,

33:16.362 --> 33:18.330
that The Brotherhood
can move it,

33:18.430 --> 33:19.598
you know, whatever it is.

33:19.698 --> 33:25.504
If it's good, it's
pure, we can move it.

33:25.604 --> 33:27.139
- [Travis] The cops
used to come in there,

33:27.239 --> 33:29.108
trying to rouse people
and bust people,

33:29.208 --> 33:33.145
and it was just a big
game of cops and robbers.

33:33.245 --> 33:36.182
- Neil Purcell pulls into
Dodge City, you know,

33:36.282 --> 33:40.252
and were smokin' the hooka
at one of the hotels.

33:40.352 --> 33:42.621
He came running in
there all by himself,

33:42.721 --> 33:43.822
"You're all under arrest!"

33:43.922 --> 33:45.457
Somebody pushed him
into the swimming pool

33:45.557 --> 33:46.692
in his uniform,

33:46.792 --> 33:48.360
and we grabbed the hooka
and everybody left.

33:48.460 --> 33:49.861
By the time he got
out of the pool,

33:49.961 --> 33:50.796
nobody was there.

33:50.896 --> 33:53.665
He fucking hated us.

33:53.765 --> 33:55.101
In those days, you know,

33:55.201 --> 33:59.305
most people would really
bow to authority's rule,

33:59.405 --> 34:01.373
but we didn't.

34:01.473 --> 34:02.808
We refused to behave,

34:02.908 --> 34:05.811
or even to pretend to
behave, we refused to.

34:05.911 --> 34:08.013
You know, it was just
like in your face,

34:08.114 --> 34:11.617
"No, we're gonna
be the way we are."

34:11.717 --> 34:13.819
We were gettin' stoned,
we were smokin' dope,

34:13.918 --> 34:17.723
takin' acid, pursuing
a spiritual life.

34:17.822 --> 34:24.230
(dramatic trippy music)

34:24.330 --> 34:27.032
Everything grows organically.

34:27.132 --> 34:30.702
You start selling acid to
10 people, then 100 people,

34:30.802 --> 34:32.371
then thousands of people,

34:32.471 --> 34:36.775
and pretty soon
you have a demand.

34:36.875 --> 34:41.280
These guys Nick, Sam, and Tim
Scully made a bunch of acid.

34:45.317 --> 34:47.186
It was the largest
amount of acid

34:47.286 --> 34:48.853
that was available for sale

34:48.954 --> 34:51.056
that was real, real good,
that we knew of, and so--

34:51.157 --> 34:52.724
- They wanted The Brotherhood
to be the distributors

34:52.824 --> 34:53.925
of the LSD.

34:54.025 --> 34:56.362
Up until that point,
the main distributors

34:56.462 --> 34:58.430
were the Hells Angels.

34:58.530 --> 35:00.332
- [Michael R.] We
wanted the exclusive.

35:00.432 --> 35:01.900
You don't want five
people to have this.

35:02.000 --> 35:05.404
You want one group to have it.

35:05.504 --> 35:07.606
We saw something in each other,

35:07.706 --> 35:09.608
Nick, and I, and Johnny.

35:09.708 --> 35:12.944
And that was it,
we were the guys.

35:13.044 --> 35:15.247
- [Voiceover] So many
miraculous things happened,

35:15.347 --> 35:18.350
that made it possible
to do the things we did.

35:18.450 --> 35:22.954
It feels like there was
divine intervention involved.

35:23.054 --> 35:24.290
- They came up with these bags,

35:24.390 --> 35:27.593
these old bags of yellow tabs,

35:27.693 --> 35:30.262
and orange tabs,

35:30.362 --> 35:32.798
and blue tabs.

35:32.898 --> 35:35.701
For some reason, everyone
liked the orange ones.

35:35.801 --> 35:38.404
- We had it all in
the trunk of this car,

35:38.504 --> 35:39.805
and turned on the radio,

35:39.905 --> 35:41.907
and there was Back
on the Street Again,

35:42.007 --> 35:43.775
by the Sunshine Company.

35:43.875 --> 35:46.445
- And they named
'em Orange Sunshine.

35:46.545 --> 35:52.484
- It became, like
overnight famous.

35:52.584 --> 35:56.121
I remember flying back east
with a small duffle bag

35:56.222 --> 35:59.425
that had baggies
of Orange Sunshine.

35:59.525 --> 36:01.660
And you know, it'd
just take five hours

36:01.760 --> 36:03.795
to get it from the west coast
and it'd be on the east coast

36:03.895 --> 36:05.297
as fast as the plane lands,

36:05.397 --> 36:08.500
and pretty soon the acid
hits the street that night.

36:12.538 --> 36:14.640
Chuck Scott, he
was kind of the one

36:14.740 --> 36:18.310
that got the New York
Market established for us.

36:18.410 --> 36:20.812
And we had people
in Laguna Beach

36:20.912 --> 36:24.850
that sold a lot of
acid on the west coast.

36:24.950 --> 36:25.951
* What'd you take

36:26.051 --> 36:27.085
* Orange Sunshine

36:27.185 --> 36:28.086
* Do you want more

36:28.186 --> 36:29.921
* Yeah yeah

36:30.021 --> 36:31.857
- Orange Sunshine

36:31.957 --> 36:33.825
became synonymous
with The Brotherhood.

36:33.925 --> 36:36.462
- It became a household
name damn quick.

36:36.562 --> 36:38.464
Sunshine was far more popular

36:38.564 --> 36:40.999
than say, Windowpane,
Purple Haze,

36:41.099 --> 36:44.002
or other things
that were around.

36:44.102 --> 36:46.338
- [Michael K.] The Grateful
Dead was always in love

36:46.438 --> 36:47.539
with The Brotherhood,

36:47.639 --> 36:49.608
because although
their music was great,

36:49.708 --> 36:52.944
it was even greater
with Orange Sunshine.

36:56.982 --> 36:59.318
- [Michael R.] People in
Hollywood were interested.

36:59.418 --> 37:01.186
People came from all over.

37:01.287 --> 37:03.289
- Acid, Sunshine?

37:03.389 --> 37:04.990
- It was happening
in San Francisco.

37:05.090 --> 37:06.224
It was happening in Amsterdam,

37:06.325 --> 37:07.826
in England, and Germany.

37:07.926 --> 37:09.961
The kids, all over the world,

37:10.061 --> 37:12.197
got this LSD at the same time.

37:12.298 --> 37:15.033
- [Voiceover] Paul, how
often have you taken LSD?

37:15.133 --> 37:17.035
- About four times.

37:17.135 --> 37:19.070
- [Voiceover] Where
did you get it from?

37:19.170 --> 37:20.171
- Oh, you know, I mean,

37:20.272 --> 37:21.673
if I was to say
where I got it from,

37:21.773 --> 37:22.874
you know it's illegal
and everything,

37:22.974 --> 37:24.843
it's silly to say then.

37:24.943 --> 37:26.912
- It was in every
city there was,

37:27.012 --> 37:28.246
and it had a name,

37:28.347 --> 37:29.915
and you know, the
Orange Sunshine.

37:30.015 --> 37:31.417
- [Voiceover] I took some acid,

37:31.517 --> 37:34.753
and they were these
little orange pills.

37:34.853 --> 37:35.921
- Were they barrel-shaped?

37:36.021 --> 37:37.523
- [Voiceover] Uh, yes.

37:37.623 --> 37:39.725
- Okay, right, you did some
Orange Sunshine, Peter.

37:39.825 --> 37:40.926
(laughing)

37:41.026 --> 37:46.832
(funky music)

37:46.932 --> 37:49.067
- [Michael R.] We
eclipsed everything.

37:49.167 --> 37:54.840
You know, we were
the Coca-Cola of LSD.

37:54.940 --> 37:57.709
- I never sold LSD or
smuggled it to make money.

37:57.809 --> 37:59.445
Ever, I can honestly say that.

37:59.545 --> 38:02.548
- Most of us said, "Hey,
the LSD should be free."

38:02.648 --> 38:04.049
That was John's dream.

38:04.149 --> 38:06.117
John's dream was everybody
did LSD for free.

38:06.217 --> 38:09.087
He said it should be in
gum machines on the corner.

38:09.187 --> 38:12.090
- When more money came in,
it didn't matter to us.

38:12.190 --> 38:15.427
The money just afforded us
to try and make more acid.

38:15.527 --> 38:17.629
Nobody was living
high on the hog,

38:17.729 --> 38:20.432
and had Cadillacs or fancy cars.

38:20.532 --> 38:22.768
I mean, I drove my old pickup.

38:22.868 --> 38:26.972
- People maintained the
same spiritual values.

38:27.072 --> 38:29.107
We just got bigger and we just,

38:29.207 --> 38:32.644
it made the machine
grow in a organic way.

38:32.744 --> 38:36.247
We made a lot of LSD,
a whole lot of it.

38:36.348 --> 38:39.284
(crowd cheering)

38:54.533 --> 38:57.969
- [Carol] At that point, you
could feel the police presence,

38:58.069 --> 39:00.806
snooping around and
asking questions,

39:00.906 --> 39:03.074
and watching people.

39:03.174 --> 39:04.910
- When you add the element
of what we're doing

39:05.010 --> 39:06.311
is very, very risky.

39:06.412 --> 39:07.946
Don't forget the fear part,

39:08.046 --> 39:11.316
and the prayers of "I hope we
don't get caught doin' this,

39:11.417 --> 39:12.951
"'cause this isn't ...

39:13.051 --> 39:15.687
"This isn't a platinum
record we're doing here.

39:15.787 --> 39:19.124
"This is something that could
send you to jail forever."

39:19.224 --> 39:20.826
- Cops, or narcs,

39:20.926 --> 39:23.094
or whoever they who were
would sit out in their cars

39:23.194 --> 39:26.131
and just watch people
coming in and going out.

39:26.231 --> 39:27.933
Trying to figure who's who,

39:28.033 --> 39:32.571
and hook who up to what and ...

39:32.671 --> 39:39.177
Oh good luck.

39:39.277 --> 39:41.212
- The Brotherhood was known more

39:41.312 --> 39:43.615
as a mystical organization.

39:43.715 --> 39:45.451
There were a lot of
people that said,

39:45.551 --> 39:47.819
"It doesn't really
exist, It's not real."

39:47.919 --> 39:49.488
- I never allowed
my picture taken,

39:49.588 --> 39:51.623
so people might know my name,

39:51.723 --> 39:55.126
but they wouldn't know
what I looked like.

39:55.226 --> 39:56.394
- After my first couple,

39:56.495 --> 39:58.163
my first trip or
two to Afghanistan,

39:58.263 --> 40:01.232
I decided we should probably
start getting fake ID.

40:01.332 --> 40:05.370
And, it was really
easy in those days.

40:08.406 --> 40:10.976
- [Michael R.] We had blank
Social Security cards,

40:11.076 --> 40:12.143
so you could fill in a number

40:12.243 --> 40:13.979
on the Social Security
card if you want.

40:14.079 --> 40:15.647
And what you do with
the birth certificate,

40:15.747 --> 40:17.516
is you could erase everything
on the birth certificate

40:17.616 --> 40:19.551
and put in other numbers
and make a copy of it,

40:19.651 --> 40:20.986
and then kind of
make it official.

40:21.086 --> 40:22.721
Put a stamp in there
and then emboss it,

40:22.821 --> 40:24.322
and it worked.

40:24.422 --> 40:25.991
- [Voiceover] The
idea was to travel

40:26.091 --> 40:27.325
under a fictitious name

40:27.425 --> 40:28.894
in case something happened
in a foreign country,

40:28.994 --> 40:30.829
and you could pay your
way out over there,

40:30.929 --> 40:32.931
so it wouldn't
reverberate back here

40:33.031 --> 40:34.432
and get us in trouble here.

40:34.533 --> 40:37.202
- We were using the
names of dead people

40:37.302 --> 40:39.437
and going and getting passports.

40:39.538 --> 40:43.609
I had four passports of
my own and three fakes.

40:43.709 --> 40:45.010
- I can remember going up to LA

40:45.110 --> 40:47.679
to the Passport Bureau one time,

40:47.779 --> 40:49.080
and I changed my appearance.

40:49.180 --> 40:51.116
I got some glasses that were
just plain glass though,

40:51.216 --> 40:53.919
stage glasses, and
changed my hair.

40:54.019 --> 40:56.187
I went in there and said, "I
need an expedited passport,

40:56.287 --> 40:57.623
"I'm leaving tomorrow."

40:57.723 --> 40:59.357
For an extra 20 bucks, man.

40:59.457 --> 41:02.594
"Okay", (mumbles) walked
out with a passport,

41:02.694 --> 41:04.696
right then, same day.

41:04.796 --> 41:07.365
Went out, went to a hotel room,

41:07.465 --> 41:10.201
changed my appearance,
completely.

41:10.301 --> 41:12.403
Went back the same day,

41:12.504 --> 41:14.105
went in a different cube,

41:14.205 --> 41:15.707
got in a different line,

41:15.807 --> 41:17.142
and got another passport,

41:17.242 --> 41:18.944
in the same office
in the same day,

41:19.044 --> 41:20.145
under two different IDs.

41:20.245 --> 41:21.312
No computers,

41:21.412 --> 41:22.981
there was not cross-referencing.

41:23.081 --> 41:24.115
- So, we were able to function

41:24.215 --> 41:29.020
right under their
nose, basically.

41:29.120 --> 41:32.090
- [Ron] We went on to
smuggle more Afghani hash,

41:32.190 --> 41:33.424
than anybody.

41:33.525 --> 41:34.926
We did big things.

41:35.026 --> 41:36.828
2400 pounds at a time.

41:36.928 --> 41:38.063
We weren't fuckin' around.

41:38.163 --> 41:40.265
We did one and
another and another.

41:40.365 --> 41:42.568
- A couple brothers
would fly to Germany.

41:42.668 --> 41:44.469
Get a car into Afghanistan,

41:44.570 --> 41:46.738
meet up with the
Tilkai brothers,

41:46.838 --> 41:47.839
all this kind of stuff.

41:47.939 --> 41:50.609
Work out a deal,
200, 300, 500 pounds.

41:50.709 --> 41:52.177
After the dope was loaded,

41:52.277 --> 41:54.145
seal, weld 'em all back up,

41:54.245 --> 41:56.114
and maybe have it
shipped to Seattle.

41:56.214 --> 42:00.619
The drive it from Seattle,
Portland down to Laguna.

42:00.719 --> 42:02.120
They were not dummies.

42:02.220 --> 42:05.591
They had some smart
people in there,

42:05.691 --> 42:08.026
but they're all crooks.

42:08.126 --> 42:11.062
(mellow music)

42:31.249 --> 42:35.286
- [Ron] Winter of '67,
Timothy moved to Laguna.

42:35.386 --> 42:38.256
He came out and joined us.

42:38.356 --> 42:40.158
- Tim saw in the brotherhood,

42:40.258 --> 42:43.228
an actualization
of his own dreams,

42:43.328 --> 42:44.796
of his own imagination,

42:44.896 --> 42:46.632
and he loved it,

42:46.732 --> 42:48.533
and they loved him.

42:48.634 --> 42:50.335
- Timothy was a focal point,

42:50.435 --> 42:53.471
a spiritual focal point
that was necessary.

42:53.571 --> 42:55.306
And he was brilliant.

42:55.406 --> 42:59.878
And his spiritual
insight was profound.

42:59.978 --> 43:02.814
You know, John Griggs was
a holy, holy, holy man,

43:02.914 --> 43:06.351
and Timothy had a big
influence on John Griggs,

43:06.451 --> 43:09.988
but John Griggs had a bigger
influence on Timothy Leary.

43:10.088 --> 43:12.257
- [Carol] Timothy Leary
looked up to Johnny

43:12.357 --> 43:14.225
as a spiritual being.

43:14.325 --> 43:17.696
They both had the same
vision and the same dream,

43:17.796 --> 43:22.167
to turn the world on.

43:22.267 --> 43:26.237
The energy was moving so
fast at that particular time.

43:26.337 --> 43:28.373
- It got to a point where it ...

43:28.473 --> 43:32.744
If somebody had some LSD,
or some pot, or some hash,

43:32.844 --> 43:35.080
and they said this was
from The Brotherhood,

43:35.180 --> 43:36.181
that's all they needed to say.

43:36.281 --> 43:40.418
It would be sold quick.

43:40.518 --> 43:42.053
- [Michael R.] It
was starting to slip

43:42.153 --> 43:45.256
into a different gear.

43:45.356 --> 43:47.425
- Dodge City had been
taken over by more hippies,

43:47.525 --> 43:49.895
and rock 'n rollin',

43:49.995 --> 43:53.331
probably crazier than ever.

43:53.431 --> 43:54.465
- [Voiceover] More
and more people

43:54.565 --> 43:56.034
were peripherally
involved with us,

43:56.134 --> 43:57.568
and then you started
hearing people say,

43:57.669 --> 43:58.870
"You know so and so?"

43:58.970 --> 44:00.538
And I'd say, "No, I
don't know that person."

44:00.638 --> 44:02.040
"Well, they're
Brotherhood members."

44:02.140 --> 44:03.742
- It wasn't for
the whole anymore.

44:03.842 --> 44:06.477
It was a group of a
bunch of smugglers

44:06.577 --> 44:07.478
that worked together.

44:07.578 --> 44:08.747
That was a whole 'nother thing.

44:08.847 --> 44:13.218
That's kind of a
business, in a way.

44:13.318 --> 44:14.720
Police were starting to go,

44:14.820 --> 44:18.423
"Oh my God this is getting
out of control, you know?"

44:18.523 --> 44:20.391
They're having big
public meetings

44:20.491 --> 44:23.561
with a few thousand
people showing up.

44:23.661 --> 44:24.896
- [Voiceover] The
game we played before

44:24.996 --> 44:26.131
was just cat and mouse,

44:26.231 --> 44:27.665
and we were always winning.

44:27.766 --> 44:30.668
Things got a little
more serious after that.

44:30.769 --> 44:32.270
- They just wanted
us outta there.

44:32.370 --> 44:37.208
Laguna was tired of
the hippie scene.

44:37.308 --> 44:39.277
- Mystic Arts World was torched

44:39.377 --> 44:41.813
by the elders of Laguna Beach.

44:41.913 --> 44:44.182
They arsoned our store.

44:44.282 --> 44:47.418
They threw a fire bomb
through the fucking sky light,

44:47.518 --> 44:51.156
and it smoke damaged everything.

44:51.256 --> 44:55.260
And it was way too
hard to reopen.

44:55.360 --> 44:57.863
The writing on the wall
was very clear to everyone.

44:57.963 --> 45:02.167
It was probably that
those days were over.

45:02.267 --> 45:05.203
(mellow music)

45:10.608 --> 45:13.278
- [Travis] The spring '68
is when we bought a ranch

45:13.378 --> 45:17.348
in Idyllwild, California
called Fobes Ranch.

45:17.448 --> 45:20.151
It was an experiment
in communal living.

45:20.251 --> 45:22.854
We were trying to find
this ideal lifestyle,

45:22.954 --> 45:24.522
and it was like
everybody contributing,

45:24.622 --> 45:28.359
everybody pitching in,
whatever you can give.

45:28.459 --> 45:29.995
We did everything together.

45:30.095 --> 45:32.463
You know, we cooked
together, ate together,

45:32.563 --> 45:35.033
you know, had our
ceremonies together.

45:35.133 --> 45:37.869
- The whole group, the
whole thing, it was family.

45:37.969 --> 45:41.039
We were all a family.

45:41.139 --> 45:44.509
Family values, that's what
we tried to cultivate,

45:44.609 --> 45:48.613
and that was a lot
of Johnny's goal.

45:48.713 --> 45:51.416
Everyone of my children,
from day one up,

45:51.516 --> 45:54.485
they knew exactly
what was going on.

45:54.585 --> 45:57.856
You know, they were
part of the movement.

45:57.956 --> 46:00.391
If my children were
playing with the

46:00.491 --> 46:02.360
outside of these realms,

46:02.460 --> 46:05.997
they knew not to talk
about what went on,

46:06.097 --> 46:10.635
and they were all very,
I would say, savvy.

46:10.735 --> 46:15.273
They were miniature hippies.

46:15.373 --> 46:20.178
- [Michael R.] The vision
was always to produce LSD,

46:20.278 --> 46:23.348
but once we got to a
certain stage with that,

46:23.448 --> 46:27.552
and Johnny saw I was
able to take care of it,

46:27.652 --> 46:28.887
he moved back.

46:28.987 --> 46:31.522
He wanted to live a
more domestic life,

46:31.622 --> 46:37.195
and I took over for him with
the traveling and all of that.

46:37.295 --> 46:39.730
- I was always trying to
find Michael a girlfriend,

46:39.831 --> 46:43.534
'cause he was a
sincere, neat guy.

46:43.634 --> 46:47.538
- I would have probably
been a lot more peaceful,

46:47.638 --> 46:51.409
if I was just pursuing my
spiritual life at the ranch,

46:51.509 --> 46:57.148
but I was obeying
a higher calling.

46:57.248 --> 46:58.383
We were successful.

46:58.483 --> 47:02.320
We sold everything
and we got to where

47:02.420 --> 47:05.590
we were ready to
take the next step,

47:05.690 --> 47:08.393
which was make more.

47:08.493 --> 47:12.397
So, we bought a house
close to Palm Springs,

47:12.497 --> 47:15.400
and we set up a lab in there.

47:28.446 --> 47:31.616
- Everybody took off to
Afghanistan to do these scams.

47:31.716 --> 47:33.284
Well, we were tired of
doing these Volkswagens

47:33.384 --> 47:35.954
and getting 400, 500
pounds in them, right?

47:36.054 --> 47:38.356
So, we find the finest
motorhome we can,

47:38.456 --> 47:40.591
and I go out to Pomona
and we buy a Lazy Days,

47:40.691 --> 47:42.593
and we get this guy
Al that was in prison,

47:42.693 --> 47:43.929
a Mexican welder,

47:44.029 --> 47:46.297
and he does the car
just like we want.

47:46.397 --> 47:48.199
I put stash places everywhere.

47:48.299 --> 47:52.503
There was probably ten
different places to stash.

47:52.603 --> 47:54.605
We did 1300 pounds in that one.

47:54.705 --> 47:59.177
It was the first big one.

47:59.277 --> 48:03.448
(upbeat hippy music)

48:03.548 --> 48:07.185
- Summer of '68, I went
back to Afghanistan

48:07.285 --> 48:09.921
to get another load.

48:10.021 --> 48:12.057
Mike Henson and David Hall,

48:12.157 --> 48:15.060
they hollowed out a spot
in these two surfboards.

48:15.160 --> 48:20.065
And they could just
pack 'em with hash.

48:20.165 --> 48:21.466
So, I took 'em along.

48:21.566 --> 48:23.034
Strapped 'em to
the top of the VW.

48:23.134 --> 48:25.636
Two surfboards in the
dead of winter in Europe,

48:25.736 --> 48:26.871
drove through the Alps,

48:26.972 --> 48:29.574
and down and across all
the way to Afghanistan.

48:29.674 --> 48:31.342
They were really out of place,

48:31.442 --> 48:33.044
and I had a wife and
a little kid with me,

48:33.144 --> 48:35.546
a little girl with me.

48:35.646 --> 48:36.647
* I'm waiting for a man

48:36.747 --> 48:40.051
* From Afghanistan to come

48:40.151 --> 48:42.487
* He got a kilo in the
bottom of a suitcase

48:42.587 --> 48:45.690
* In a cabin son

48:45.790 --> 48:48.493
* If the captain comes
you don't give him no lip

48:48.593 --> 48:51.997
* But you pick it up later
and you know the trip *

48:52.097 --> 48:53.664
- When we came back,

48:53.764 --> 48:56.367
we shipped the surfboards
as unaccompanied baggage.

48:56.467 --> 48:58.269
We got home and
everything was cool.

48:58.369 --> 49:00.238
United Airlines had
had some kind of strike

49:00.338 --> 49:01.906
in their cargo thing,

49:02.007 --> 49:05.576
and the two surfboards sat
out in the yard in the sun.

49:05.676 --> 49:07.245
And they were in canvas bags,

49:07.345 --> 49:09.747
that were made out
of denim, blue denim.

49:09.847 --> 49:12.417
And the hash started goin' off,

49:12.517 --> 49:15.086
started decaying in
there and swelled up.

49:15.186 --> 49:16.354
So, when the strike was over

49:16.454 --> 49:17.688
they went to ship
the boards to LA,

49:17.788 --> 49:18.789
someone picked 'em up

49:18.889 --> 49:20.225
and stuff was rattling
around in there.

49:20.325 --> 49:22.727
They cut 'em open,
they found the hash.

49:22.827 --> 49:25.263
They shipped it on over,
had me come pick it up.

49:25.363 --> 49:26.731
Customs agents even
helped me load it

49:26.831 --> 49:27.865
and tie it on the car,

49:27.965 --> 49:30.635
rather than bust me
right on the spot,

49:30.735 --> 49:34.439
and then they followed me.

49:34.539 --> 49:38.143
- The rule at the ranch was,
not to endanger the ranch.

49:38.243 --> 49:41.146
You know, don't
bring the load there.

49:41.246 --> 49:44.649
Travis, God bless his soul,

49:44.749 --> 49:47.552
has brought more
heat down people

49:47.652 --> 49:51.289
than anyone I've ever known.

49:51.389 --> 49:54.425
The feds followed
them all the way,

49:54.525 --> 49:56.627
all the way to
the fucking ranch,

49:56.727 --> 49:59.630
and it was a disaster.

49:59.730 --> 50:02.167
- They had a plane spotting me.

50:02.267 --> 50:03.901
And when I went through
the locked gate,

50:04.001 --> 50:05.670
and got part way up the road,

50:05.770 --> 50:06.837
I remember turning back

50:06.937 --> 50:07.938
and looking back
down in the valley,

50:08.039 --> 50:09.940
and seeing this train of cars,

50:10.041 --> 50:13.611
just coming up the dirt
road, just hauling ass.

50:13.711 --> 50:14.779
And they swooped on us,

50:14.879 --> 50:16.147
guns drawn and
everything and got us.

50:16.247 --> 50:17.815
And then they wanted to
see what was up this road,

50:17.915 --> 50:20.385
where I was going.

50:20.485 --> 50:22.787
- The next thing I
know, Travis pulls up,

50:22.887 --> 50:25.156
and down comes the helicopter

50:25.256 --> 50:28.093
that had followed
him all the way in.

50:28.193 --> 50:31.596
We looked out the windows
and went, "Holy God!"

50:31.696 --> 50:36.334
You know, they are so here.

50:36.434 --> 50:38.436
- The cops pull right up in
the front of the ranch there.

50:38.536 --> 50:40.438
There's all these
hippies everywhere.

50:40.538 --> 50:41.872
You know, they don't
even know what to think.

50:41.972 --> 50:44.709
What the heck's this?

50:44.809 --> 50:46.577
And then they took me away.

50:52.617 --> 50:54.119
- Everything was blown.

50:54.219 --> 50:55.686
Now passports were checked.

50:55.786 --> 50:57.021
What was shipped back?

50:57.122 --> 50:58.823
Those surfboards,
what was in 'em?

50:58.923 --> 51:02.627
I mean everything,
now they know.

51:02.727 --> 51:05.663
Now, legal things are
starting to happen.

51:05.763 --> 51:09.734
A lot of money that was
earned went into legal defense

51:09.834 --> 51:12.337
for whoever it was
that was in trouble.

51:12.437 --> 51:13.838
We were a family, you know.

51:13.938 --> 51:15.973
Nobody, nobody suffered.

51:21.011 --> 51:23.514
- [Michael R.] Timothy Leary
and a small contingency

51:23.614 --> 51:24.849
of people from Millbrook

51:24.949 --> 51:27.818
came to live at the ranch.

51:27.918 --> 51:30.688
- Timothy's
philosophy is Taoism.

51:30.788 --> 51:33.558
Taoism wants you to stay down.

51:33.658 --> 51:36.261
Stay in the background,
behind the scenes.

51:36.361 --> 51:38.329
And when Timothy decided
to run for governor,

51:38.429 --> 51:41.332
it was almost against everything
he'd been teaching us.

51:41.432 --> 51:43.334
- I'm going to run
for the governorship

51:43.434 --> 51:45.002
of the state of California.

51:45.102 --> 51:47.772
I think that we
need a new party,

51:47.872 --> 51:50.241
and by party I mean party.

51:50.341 --> 51:52.710
- We were like, what?

51:52.810 --> 51:55.513
This guy's sitting in the
teepee, next to the pear tree,

51:55.613 --> 51:57.282
in the meadow at our ranch,

51:57.382 --> 51:59.250
should not be
running for governor.

51:59.350 --> 52:01.686
* When you make love

52:01.786 --> 52:04.222
* Play it to me

52:04.322 --> 52:06.191
- [Carol] Johnny and I, when
we got back to the teepee,

52:06.291 --> 52:07.858
we both cried,

52:07.958 --> 52:10.728
because it was
something had changed.

52:10.828 --> 52:14.365
It wasn't going in the
direction that we wanted.

52:14.465 --> 52:16.967
- We had this engagement
in the real world out here,

52:17.067 --> 52:18.569
because we were
trying to change it,

52:18.669 --> 52:21.138
but we didn't want to
be governor, you know.

52:21.239 --> 52:22.773
I might have to put suits on

52:22.873 --> 52:24.575
and dress up like I'm straight,

52:24.675 --> 52:28.613
but that don't mean I
have to be straight.

52:28.713 --> 52:30.248
- [Travis] John Lennon
wrote Come Together

52:30.348 --> 52:34.285
as Timothy Leary's
campaign song.

52:34.385 --> 52:36.120
People hear that on the
radio all the time now.

52:36.221 --> 52:37.922
That song plays well,
every theme song

52:38.022 --> 52:40.891
for Timothy Leary's
governor race.

52:40.991 --> 52:43.093
He was gonna run against
Ronald Reagan as governor.

52:43.194 --> 52:44.829
- Let the kids get high.

52:44.929 --> 52:46.664
As a matter of fact,
President Nixon,

52:46.764 --> 52:50.000
why don't we all
turn on together.

52:50.100 --> 52:51.168
- [Michael K.] At the time,

52:51.269 --> 52:53.938
the government probably
feared Tim Leary

52:54.038 --> 52:56.106
more than they feared anybody.

52:56.207 --> 52:57.808
Nixon thought that dope dealers

52:57.908 --> 53:00.311
were among the worst
criminals on Earth.

53:00.411 --> 53:02.747
- We must wage what I
would call total war

53:02.847 --> 53:05.015
against public enemy number one

53:05.115 --> 53:06.451
in the United States,

53:06.551 --> 53:09.454
the problem of dangerous drugs.

53:09.554 --> 53:10.955
- [Travis] That was the
beginning of the end.

53:11.055 --> 53:13.991
That was when they
decided to target Tim.

53:14.091 --> 53:16.927
They're gonna get him
one way or the other.

53:26.971 --> 53:28.105
- This one night,

53:28.205 --> 53:31.276
and it was December 26th of '68,

53:31.376 --> 53:33.778
at about 11:00 P.M.,

53:33.878 --> 53:38.849
I by myself, black and white
police unit, full uniform,

53:38.949 --> 53:41.652
and here's this car stopped

53:41.752 --> 53:45.356
facing me in the
middle of the road.

53:45.456 --> 53:48.359
So, I walk over and
I tap on the window,

53:48.459 --> 53:50.295
and all of a sudden
the window comes down.

53:50.395 --> 53:53.030
And this grey-haired guy says,

53:53.130 --> 53:56.200
"What's the problem
officer?", real nice.

53:56.301 --> 53:58.135
And I looked at him

53:58.235 --> 54:01.706
and I'm thinkin', "Holy moly,

54:01.806 --> 54:04.875
"this looks like Leary."

54:04.975 --> 54:07.812
I said, "May I see
your driver's license?"

54:07.912 --> 54:09.246
"Oh sure", real nice.

54:09.347 --> 54:12.249
Come, take out, and
all of a sudden, bingo.

54:12.350 --> 54:15.753
Timothy Leary,
1230 Queens Street,

54:15.853 --> 54:17.888
Berkeley, California.

54:17.988 --> 54:19.924
I said, "Well, Mr. Leary,

54:20.024 --> 54:24.395
"I smell the odor of burned
marijuana", which I did.

54:24.495 --> 54:27.031
I tell Leary, "Step
out of the car.

54:27.131 --> 54:28.766
"This is a narcotic
investigation."

54:28.866 --> 54:31.201
He is just coming unglued.

54:31.302 --> 54:33.203
You don't have probable cause.

54:33.304 --> 54:35.039
This is an illegal stop.

54:35.139 --> 54:36.874
This is an illegal
this and that.

54:36.974 --> 54:38.509
I go in his car,

54:38.609 --> 54:40.545
obvious place to look
first, the ashtray.

54:40.645 --> 54:43.781
There's two little
roaches there.

54:43.881 --> 54:46.951
Pull 'em out, and I said,

54:47.051 --> 54:49.920
"You're under
arrest, Mr. Leary."

54:50.020 --> 54:52.189
- [Voiceover] Dr. Leary's
political ambitions

54:52.289 --> 54:53.524
were cut short,

54:53.624 --> 54:55.526
when Governor Reagan
had Leary arrested,

54:55.626 --> 54:57.595
and sentenced to
30 years in jail,

54:57.695 --> 55:01.298
for possession of $10
worth of marijuana.

55:08.673 --> 55:13.043
- Tim was in prison and
we were taking his appeal.

55:13.143 --> 55:16.781
He had been arrested in
Texas, bullshit charges.

55:16.881 --> 55:19.717
He was arrested in
California twice,

55:19.817 --> 55:21.552
again no real charges,

55:21.652 --> 55:25.623
but he was a political
person who they feared.

55:25.723 --> 55:28.393
And they would do anything
to get him off the street,

55:28.493 --> 55:29.994
get him into prison,

55:30.094 --> 55:32.129
and try and shut him down.

55:32.229 --> 55:34.932
- Timothy was a
spiritual leader,

55:35.032 --> 55:39.437
and to keep the path
going of Orange Sunshine,

55:39.537 --> 55:41.906
we did the outrageous
other option

55:42.006 --> 55:43.674
that no one thinks of:

55:43.774 --> 55:46.844
prison break.

55:46.944 --> 55:48.813
The first thing that we did is

55:48.913 --> 55:50.981
looked at the prison
that Timothy was in

55:51.081 --> 55:54.652
and started working with
this guy on the inside,

55:54.752 --> 55:57.822
"What is the best way
to get out of here?"

55:57.922 --> 55:58.956
That was over the fence,

55:59.056 --> 56:01.692
just a straight
up over the fence.

56:01.792 --> 56:04.328
There was a place that
was perfect to go over,

56:04.429 --> 56:06.130
the way the trees were situated,

56:06.230 --> 56:09.033
the road was virtually
right fucking there.

56:09.133 --> 56:11.969
And Timothy needed to start
doing pullups and things

56:12.069 --> 56:13.838
so he had better
upper body strength,

56:13.938 --> 56:17.475
and could get his
ass over that fence.

56:17.575 --> 56:19.544
- [Carol] I remember talks

56:19.644 --> 56:21.779
around the table
of the main house.

56:21.879 --> 56:24.048
"Who was gonna fly him
from here to there?"

56:24.148 --> 56:28.085
- This went on for six months,
nine months or something.

56:34.124 --> 56:37.127
(eery music)

57:05.990 --> 57:09.760
You know, when you
take LSD with people,

57:09.860 --> 57:15.466
you feel every thought,
every emotion all together.

57:15.566 --> 57:21.238
And so, when you take LSD with a

57:21.338 --> 57:24.108
advanced spiritual being,

57:24.208 --> 57:26.176
you're gonna know
about it right away.

57:26.276 --> 57:28.679
You will have a
different kind of trip.

57:28.779 --> 57:32.750
And that's what Johnny was.

57:32.850 --> 57:34.251
- See, the higher
doses you take,

57:34.351 --> 57:36.086
the more far out it gets.

57:36.186 --> 57:38.188
And it can get pretty scary too.

57:38.288 --> 57:40.558
John was always there for
when it got really heavy.

57:40.658 --> 57:43.360
John would be the guy
that could reassure you,

57:43.460 --> 57:45.930
grab your hand and just
touch you to make it feel,

57:46.030 --> 57:48.432
make you go ma, the
bad stuff go away,

57:48.533 --> 57:53.771
just with his presence.

57:53.871 --> 57:57.241
- God always chooses
unlikely things, you know.

57:57.341 --> 57:58.743
Holy men are not

57:58.843 --> 58:01.411
always what you
really might think of.

58:01.512 --> 58:03.213
They're ...

58:03.313 --> 58:05.149
A good holy man
has got some flaws,

58:05.249 --> 58:06.751
and something wrong,

